equation_narrative.headline: Minimal context drives alanine prediction in structurally isolated loop position
equation_narrative.story: Position 46 in ubiquitin sits in a structurally isolated loop with no detected 3D contacts or co-evolutionary partners. Through layers 1-23, the model assembles a representation from purely local sequence context (RLIF[A]GKQLE), with the logit lens showing volatile shifts between small polar (S, T) and hydrophobic (A, V, L) residues as different sequence features activate. The representation remains chemically ambiguous until layer 23, reflecting the position's lack of strong structural constraints. At layer 24-25, the decision phase begins abruptly: attention head L25:16 writes strongly from local context, and MLP neurons in layers 29-32 activate alanine-specific prediction channels. Alanine wins decisively (64%) over serine (29%), driven by the small, flexible character encoded in the local sequence window.

perception_phase.summary: Layers 1-23 show information gathering from a structurally sparse context. With zero structural contacts and zero co-evolutionary partners, the model relies entirely on local sequence. Early attention features (F1:9146, F1:5480, F1:1508) encode the immediate sequence window. The logit lens shows extreme volatility—15 lead changes through layer 23—as the representation oscillates between small polar residues (S peaks at 23% L22, T peaks at 19% L20) and small hydrophobics (A, V, L). This instability reflects genuine ambiguity: the position lacks the structural or evolutionary constraints that typically stabilize representations. By layer 18, features like F18:244 (25.8 proj) and F18:9177 (22.7 proj) encode abstract properties of small, flexible positions, but no dominant chemical character emerges until the decision phase.
perception_phase.context_character: The biochemical context is minimal and permissive: a solvent-exposed loop position with no structural packing constraints, no co-evolutionary coupling, and local sequence favoring small, flexible residues. The representation through L23 is consistent with any small amino acid (A, S, T, G) without strong preference.
key_information_sources: Structural contacts: 0 detected—position is structurally isolated in a flexible loop region
Co-evolutionary signal: 0 coupled positions—no functional constraints from distant residues
Local sequence: RLIF[A]GKQLE window encodes small-residue preference through L1-9 attention features
L18 features: F18:244 (25.8 proj, attn) and F18:9177 (22.7 proj, attn) encode loop/flexible-position character

decision_phase.summary: The decision crystallizes sharply at layers 24-25. Attention head L25:16 delivers a 2.49 projection from local sequence context, triggering the transition. MLP layers 29-32 activate alanine-specific prediction channels: N29:619 (0.89 proj for A), N29:1110 (0.81 proj for A), N31:5093 (0.94 proj for A). Alanine rises from 11% at L23 to 65% at L32, while serine (the runner-up) climbs more gradually from 15% to 29%. The final competition is between the smallest hydrophobic (A) and smallest polar (S) residues, both consistent with the flexible loop context.
decision_phase.transition: At L23-25, the representation shifts from encoding 'what's here' to committing to a specific answer. L23 shows S leading at 15.2% with A at 11.4%—both low probabilities reflecting representational ambiguity. L25 attention head 16 writes 2.49 toward A from local context, and by L29, alanine-specific MLP neurons dominate. The first high-specificity prediction features appear at L24 (F24:2079, 18.8 proj), marking the perception-to-decision boundary.

candidates.narrative: Alanine emerges as the winner through strong MLP support in layers 29-32. N29:619 (0.89 proj) and N29:1110 (0.81 proj) fire as alanine-specific prediction channels, pushing A from 10% at L29 to 65% at L32. N31:5093 (0.94 proj) provides additional decisive support. The model interprets the minimal structural context and small-residue local sequence as favoring the smallest hydrophobic amino acid. Alanine's trajectory shows it was present but weak through perception (hovering 11-20%), then surges in the decision phase when prediction neurons activate.
candidates.key_layers: Weak through L23 (11%), surges L29-32 to 65%
key_evidence: N29:619 (0.89 proj) — alanine-specific MLP neuron, strongest A writer at L29
N31:5093 (0.94 proj) — alanine-specific MLP neuron, strongest A writer at L31
L25:16 attention head (2.49 proj) — local writer triggering decision phase

candidates.narrative: Serine is the runner-up, finishing at 29%. It leads through much of the perception phase (peaks at 24% L22) because the representation is consistent with small polar residues given the loop context. In the decision phase, serine receives moderate MLP support (N29:1110 votes 0.97 for S, even more than for A), but lacks the decisive prediction channels that drive alanine. The S vs A competition reflects the model's uncertainty about whether the position favors polar or hydrophobic character in the absence of structural constraints.
key_evidence: N29:1110 (0.97 proj for S) — votes slightly more for S than A (0.81)
Leads logit lens L15-23, reflecting polar-compatible representation
F33:6701 (109.8 proj, MLP) — late feature with mixed A/S support

candidates.narrative: Threonine is an early leader, peaking at 19% at L20 when the representation is consistent with small polar residues. The logit lens shows T leading at L6, L19-20 as attention features encode loop-position character. However, T collapses in the decision phase (drops to 0.66% at L29) as MLP neurons commit to either A or S. T's early prominence reflects the representation's polar-leaning character during perception, not a genuine model belief—it simply correlates with the features being assembled.
candidates.key_layers: Peaks at L20 (19%), collapses by L29 (0.66%)
key_evidence: Peaks at 19.4% L20 during perception phase
Receives negative MLP votes at L20 (N20:4271 erases -0.40 from A)
Collapses when alanine-specific neurons activate L29+

candidates.narrative: Glycine is a minor contender, peaking at 13% at L28 before settling at 3.4%. The model briefly considers glycine as the ultimate flexible residue for this loop position. G receives transient support from MLP neurons that encode extreme flexibility (N21:3914 votes 1.15 for G), but this is overridden by neurons favoring slightly larger residues (A, S). Glycine's trajectory shows the model exploring the 'maximally flexible' hypothesis before settling on alanine as the better balance of size and flexibility.
key_evidence: N21:3914 (1.15 proj for G) — votes strongly for glycine as flexibility signal
Peaks at 12.6% L28 during late decision phase
Suppressed by alanine-specific neurons in L29-32

turning_points.description: The representation shifts from hydrophobic-leaning (A, V, L dominant L7-14) to polar-leaning (S, T lead L15-23). This reflects the model reading different aspects of the local sequence: early layers emphasize the hydrophobic neighbors (L, I, F), while mid layers emphasize the charged neighbors (R, K, E) and loop context. The logit lens shows 8 lead changes in this range, with S peaking at 24% L22. This volatility is not indecision—it's the representation encoding multiple compatible chemical characters in the absence of structural constraints.

The perception-to-decision transition occurs sharply at L24-25. L25 attention head 16 writes 2.49 from local context (99.5% local attention), triggering the shift. The logit lens shows A jumping from 11% to 14% while S drops from 15% to 14%—small absolute changes but marking the onset of commitment. F24:2079 (18.8 proj, attn) is the first high-projection feature, encoding alanine-compatible properties. MLP layer 24 contributes net +1.90 toward A, the first strongly positive MLP contribution.

The final decision crystallizes through MLP neurons in L29-32. N29:619 (0.89 proj), N29:1110 (0.81 proj), N31:5093 (0.94 proj), and N32:1235 (0.85 proj) fire as alanine-specific prediction channels, driving A from 10% to 65%. Simultaneously, MLP erasers suppress competing candidates: N30:105 erases -1.42 (votes for P, R, K—wrong chemistry), N31:1600 erases -0.73 (votes for I, V—too large). The velocity events show MLP-driven swings: L31 MLP contributes -7.52 (suppressing non-A candidates), L29 MLP contributes +2.71 (boosting A).

deep_dives.label: Early attention (L1-9)
deep_dives.caption: Examine how the model reads local sequence context in the absence of structural contacts. L1 and L9 attention features encode the immediate sequence window (RLIF[A]GKQLE). Look for features with high projections that capture small-residue preferences from neighboring positions.

deep_dives.label: Mid-layer features (L18)
deep_dives.caption: L18 features encode abstract loop-position character. F18:244 (25.8 proj) and F18:9177 (22.7 proj) likely represent flexible/exposed position encoding. These features explain why the logit lens is consistent with multiple small residues (A, S, T, G) without committing to one.

deep_dives.label: Decision trigger (L25 attn)
deep_dives.caption: L25 attention head 16 writes 2.49 from local context, triggering the perception-to-decision transition. This is the largest attention write event in the entire forward pass. Examine what specific sequence positions it reads and how this initiates commitment to alanine.

deep_dives.label: Alanine prediction neurons (L29-31)
deep_dives.caption: These layers contain the decisive alanine-specific prediction channels. N29:619 (0.89 proj), N29:1110 (0.81 proj), N31:5093 (0.94 proj) vote strongly for A. Compare their top_votes to see how they distinguish A from S (the runner-up). Also note the strong erasers (N30:105, N31:1600) that suppress wrong-chemistry candidates.

deep_dives.label: Final prediction features (L33)
deep_dives.caption: L33 features are the final prediction channels. F33:132 (120.5 proj, MLP) is the strongest alanine feature. F33:6701 (109.8 proj, MLP) likely supports both A and S (explaining why S remains at 29%). These features integrate all prior evidence into the final logit distribution.

deep_dives.label: Decision-phase velocity (L24-33)
deep_dives.caption: Track the largest logit shifts in the decision phase. L25 (+5.84, attn-driven) initiates commitment. L29 (+2.71, MLP-driven) and L31 (-7.52, MLP-driven) show MLP neurons casting decisive votes. L33 (+6.16) is the final correction. Note how attention triggers the decision but MLPs execute it.

equation_narrative.resolution: The model correctly predicts alanine for this structurally isolated loop position by assembling a minimal context from local sequence alone. With zero structural contacts and zero co-evolutionary partners, the representation remains chemically ambiguous through layer 23, oscillating between small polar (S, T) and small hydrophobic (A, V, L) residues. The decision crystallizes at L24-25 when attention head L25:16 writes strongly from local context, triggering alanine-specific MLP neurons in L29-32 (N29:619, N31:5093, N32:1235). The final 64% confidence for alanine over 29% for serine reflects the model's interpretation that the RLIF[A]GKQLE sequence window and loop-position character favor the smallest hydrophobic residue. The strongest evidence is the coordinated activation of alanine-specific prediction channels in the final MLP layers, which distinguish A from S based on subtle hydrophobic vs polar preferences encoded in the local sequence.
